        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer20504052" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2509869354553528623">This is a terrific book. The authors cover terrain which has been explored recently in a whole slew of books: loosely speaking, why we humans persistently engage in behavior patterns which do not benefit us in the long term. Their own research, at the University of Chicago, builds upon the work of Tversky and Kahneman in behavioral economics (very much in vogue this past few years). <br/><br/>In the book, they provide a funny, engaging, remarkably clear exposition of the various factors which lead us to m</span>
  <span id="freeText2509869354553528623" style="display:none">This is a terrific book. The authors cover terrain which has been explored recently in a whole slew of books: loosely speaking, why we humans persistently engage in behavior patterns which do not benefit us in the long term. Their own research, at the University of Chicago, builds upon the work of Tversky and Kahneman in behavioral economics (very much in vogue this past few years). <br /><br />In the book, they provide a funny, engaging, remarkably clear exposition of the various factors which lead us to make poor decisions. This alone would make it worth reading. What makes this book stand out though is that they actually suggest *remedies* that might help us save ourselves from our own flawed gut instincts. </span>
  <a data-text-id="2509869354553528623" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
